<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-08-05T08:45:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-08-05T08:45:00-05:00" n="534" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d534">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">817.00/5894: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Eberhardt</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-08-05T08:00:00-05:45"><hi rend="italic">August 5,
                                        1928—8 a.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 10:33
                            a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>305. On August 7th Captain Edson, proceeding up Coco River with 46
                            marines, attacked what believed to be the main body of outlaws about 20
                            miles below Wamblan, inflicting known losses on the enemy of 10 killed,
                            3 wounded. One marine named Meyer Stengel was killed and 3 wounded, the
                            latter being now cared for at Puerto Cabezas. Outlaws believed to be the
                            retreating survivors of the forces which engaged the American planes on
                            July 25th.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Eberhardt</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
